ons-proposed-changes\n\n== New Zealand ==\nNew Zealand offers a similar PRS service. New Zealand's Personal Radio Service (PRS) and 26&nbsp;MHz Citizens Band radio are very similar to Australia's UHF Citizens Band and 27&nbsp;MHz Citizens Band services.\n \nThe New Zealand Government's Ministry of Commerce introduced the UHF PRS in 1996 to allow for freely available short-range wireless communications outside the 26&nbsp;MHz CB band. The UHF (but not VHF) band was selected due to its ability to withstand atmospheric and groundwave interference unlike the existing 26&nbsp;MHz allocation.\n \nNZ PRS channels\n* http://www.uhfcb.com.au/NZ-PRS-Channels.php\n\n==See also==\n* [[Citizens band radio]]\n* [[VMB4|VMB4 Newcastle]] - An example of an Australian UHF CB Repeater\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.legislation.gov.au/Latest/F2015L00876 Radiocommunications (Citizen Band Radio Stations) Class Licence 2015] - The Australian official licence under which UHF CB operates\n* [http://www.acma.gov.au Australian Communications and Media Authority] - The Australian regulator of the radio-frequency spectrum\n* [http://www.tropinet.com/uhf-repeaters/search.html Tropinet UHF CB Repeater Database] for a listing of repeaters in Australia.\n\n{{Two-way radio}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uhf Cb}}\n[[Category:Bandplans]]\n[[Category:Radio hobbies]]\n", "name_user": "Kvng", "label": "safe", "comment": "avoid unnec redirect", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UHF_CB"}
{"title_page": "GM G platform (1995)", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2013}}\n{{main|GM G platform}}\n{{Infobox automobile platform\n| name             = GM G platform (FWD)\n| image            = Oldsmobile-Aurora.jpg\n| caption          = 2001-2003 Oldsmobile Aurora\n| aka              = G-Body\n| manufacturer     = [[General Motors]]\n| production       = 1995&ndash;2011\n| class            = [[Personal luxury car]] (Buick Riviera)<br />[[Executive car|Mid-size executive car]] ([[E-segment|E]]) (Cadillac Seville)<br />[[Full-size]] [[luxury car]] ([[F-segment|F]])\n| predecessor      = [[GM C platform (FWD)|GM C platform]] [[GM E platform]]\n| successor        = [[GM Sigma platform]] (STS/SLS)<br />[[GM Epsilon platform]]<br />[[GM Omega platform]]\n| body_style       = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]<br>2-door [[coupe]]\n| engine           = \n| transmission     = \n| front_suspension = \n| rear_suspension  = \n| wheelbase        = \n| related          = [[GM C platform (FWD)]] <br /> [[GM H platform (FWD)]] <br /> [[GM K platform (FWD)]]\n| vehicles         = \n}}\n\nThe '''[[General Motors]] G platform''' (also called '''G-Body''') [[automobile platform]] designation was used for [[front-wheel drive]] [[full-size car|full-sized]] and [[luxury car]]s between 1995 and 2011.\n\nPreviously General Motors used the [[GM G platform (RWD)]] designation for unrelated [[mid-size car|mid-sized]] cars.\n\nThe G-body (the '''GMX690''') was based on [[Cadillac]]'s [[GM K platform (FWD)|K-body]] architecture. The platform was introduced in 1995 with [[Buick Riviera]] 2-door [[coupe]] (which moved up from the [[GM E platform]]) and the [[Oldsmobile Aurora]] 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] (a new model that replaced the Riviera-derived [[Oldsmobile Toronado|Toronado]]).  By the turn of the millennium, full-sized cars from four different GM makes were using some derivative of the platform.\n\n==Platform consolidation==\nStarting with the 1997 Buick Park Avenue, GM consolidated its four large-car platforms; [[GM C platform (FWD)|C platform]], [[GM K platform (FWD)|K platform]], [[GM H platform (FWD)|H platform]], and G platform; all to the G platform. However, GM decided to retain their previous platform designations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Frame|first=Phil|title=GM H CARS MOVE TO G PLATFORM|url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19950116/ANA/501160730#axzz2TYYYR1jT|work=[[Automotive News]]|accessdate=17 May 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.autonews.com%2Fapps%2Fpbcs.dll%2Farticle%3FAID%3D%2F19950116%2FANA%2F501160730%23axzz2TYYYR1jT&date=2013-05-17|archivedate=17 May 2013|date=16 January 1995}}</ref> These legacy platform designations were used in the VIN number and official GM publications. Models designated as \"G\" went out of production for MY 1999, but successor models were sold until MY 2011. \n\nThe G-body had an extremely resilient structure. For its time, the G-body was one of the strongest unibody car frames in production (25&nbsp;Hz). This fact did not go untouted as GM literature made much of the need to use a 'frame crusher' designed to test heavy-duty truck frames to finally break the G-body structure in their crush-to-failure procedures. Vehicles built on the G platform are also noted for having [[Seat belt#Belt-in-Seat .28BIS.29|belt-in-seat]] style seat belts like the mid-size [[GMT360]] SUVs. {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} The G-body also featured four-wheel [[independent suspension]] with a [[MacPherson strut]] style front suspension and a [[semi-trailing arm]] style rear suspension that utilized [[aluminum]] control arms. All-new aluminum control arms were introduced for the front suspension for 1998. {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} The handling was further enhanced with standard front and rear [[stabilizer bar]]s and lateral links in the rear suspension to further control wheel [[Toe (automotive)|toe]]. {{citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\n===Vehicles===\n[[File:1999 Buick Riviera.jpg|250px|right|thumb|1999 Buick Riviera]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Years\n!Wheelbase\n!Model\n!Platform Name*\n|-\n|1995\u20131999||113.8&nbsp;in||[[Buick Riviera]]||GM G platform\n|-\n|1995\u20131999||113.8&nbsp;in||[[Oldsmobile Aurora]]||GM G platform\n|-\n|1997-2005||113.8&nbsp;in||[[Buick Park Avenue]]||[[GM C platform (1985)|GM C platform]]\n|-\n|1998\u20132004||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Cadillac Seville]]||[[GM K platform (1980)|GM K platform]]\n|-\n|2000\u20132005||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Buick LeSabre]]||[[GM H platform (1986)|GM H platform]]\n|-\n|2000\u20132005||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Pontiac Bonneville]]||[[GM H platform (1986)|GM H platform]]\n|-\n|2001\u20132003||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Oldsmobile Aurora]]||GM G platform\n|-\n|2000\u20132005||115.3&nbsp;in||[[Cadillac DeVille]]||[[GM K platform (1980)|GM K platform]]\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> Official designation given by GM, despite using a G platform-derivative. This name also corresponds to the 4th letter in the [[VIN]] of the vehicle.\n\n==Revision==\nThe G platform was updated for the 2006 model year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Buick Lucerne|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/news/buick-lucerne-auto-shows|work=[[Car and Driver]]|accessdate=17 May 2013|date=February 2005}}</ref>  The final car on this platform was the [[Buick Lucerne]], which ended production in June 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.just-auto.com/news/gm-axes-cadillac-dts-and-buick-lucerne_id111499.aspx|title=US: GM axes Cadillac DTS and Buick Lucerne|publisher=just-auto.com |date=2011-05-26 |accessdate=2011-06-05}}</ref>\n\n===Vehicles===\n[[File:Buick-Lucerne.jpg|right|thumb|2006 Buick Lucerne]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Years\n!Wheelbase\n!Model\n!Platform Name*\n|-\n|2006\u20132011||115.6&nbsp;in||[[Cadillac DTS]]||[[GM K platform (1980)|GM K platform]]\n|-\n|2006\u20132011||115.6&nbsp;in||[[Buick Lucerne]]||[[GM H platform (1986)|GM H platform]]\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> Official designation given by GM, despite using a G platform-derivative. This name also corresponds to the 4th letter in the [[VIN]] of the vehicle.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[http://pp.kpnet.fi/haydee/GM_VIN_codes.htm List of GM VIN codes]\n{{General Motors platforms}}\n\n[[Category:General Motors platforms|G 2]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2013}}\n{{main|GM G platform}}\n{{Infobox automobile platform\n| name             = GM G platform (FWD)\n| image            = Oldsmobile-Aurora.jpg\n| caption          = 2001-2003 Oldsmobile Aurora\n| aka              = G-Body\n| manufacturer     = [[General Motors]]\n| production       = 1995&ndash;2011\n| class            = [[Full-size]] \n| predecessor      = [[GM C platform (FWD)|GM C platform]] [[GM E platform]]\n| successor        = [[GM Sigma platform]] (STS/SLS)<br />[[GM Epsilon platform]]<br />[[GM Omega platform]]\n| body_style       = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]<br>2-door [[coupe]]\n| engine           = \n| transmission     = \n| front_suspension = \n| rear_suspension  = \n| wheelbase        = \n| related          = [[GM C platform (FWD)]] <br /> [[GM H platform (FWD)]] <br /> [[GM K platform (FWD)]]\n| vehicles         = \n}}\n\nThe '''[[General Motors]] G platform''' (also called '''G-Body''') [[automobile platform]] designation was used for [[front-wheel drive]] [[full-size car|full-sized]] and [[luxury car]]s between 1995 and 2011.\n\nPreviously General Motors used the [[GM G platform (RWD)]] designation for unrelated [[mid-size car|mid-sized]] cars.\n\nThe G-body (the '''GMX690''') was based on [[Cadillac]]'s [[GM K platform (FWD)|K-body]] architecture. The platform was introduced in 1995 with [[Buick Riviera]] 2-door [[coupe]] (which moved up from the [[GM E platform]]) and the [[Oldsmobile Aurora]] 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] (a new model that replaced the Riviera-derived [[Oldsmobile Toronado|Toronado]]).  By the turn of the millennium, full-sized cars from four different GM makes were using some derivative of the platform.\n\n==Platform consolidation==\nStarting with the 1997 Buick Park Avenue, GM consolidated its four large-car platforms; [[GM C platform (FWD)|C platform]], [[GM K platform (FWD)|K platform]], [[GM H platform (FWD)|H platform]], and G platform; all to the G platform. However, GM decided to retain their previous platform designations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Frame|first=Phil|title=GM H CARS MOVE TO G PLATFORM|url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19950116/ANA/501160730#axzz2TYYYR1jT|work=[[Automotive News]]|accessdate=17 May 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.autonews.com%2Fapps%2Fpbcs.dll%2Farticle%3FAID%3D%2F19950116%2FANA%2F501160730%23axzz2TYYYR1jT&date=2013-05-17|archivedate=17 May 2013|date=16 January 1995}}</ref> These legacy platform designations were used in the VIN number and official GM publications. Models designated as \"G\" went out of production for MY 1999, but successor models were sold until MY 2011. \n\nThe G-body had an extremely resilient structure. For its time, the G-body was one of the strongest unibody car frames in production (25&nbsp;Hz). This fact did not go untouted as GM literature made much of the need to use a 'frame crusher' designed to test heavy-duty truck frames to finally break the G-body structure in their crush-to-failure procedures. Vehicles built on the G platform are also noted for having [[Seat belt#Belt-in-Seat .28BIS.29|belt-in-seat]] style seat belts like the mid-size [[GMT360]] SUVs. {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} The G-body also featured four-wheel [[independent suspension]] with a [[MacPherson strut]] style front suspension and a [[semi-trailing arm]] style rear suspension that utilized [[aluminum]] control arms. All-new aluminum control arms were introduced for the front suspension for 1998. {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} The handling was further enhanced with standard front and rear [[stabilizer bar]]s and lateral links in the rear suspension to further control wheel [[Toe (automotive)|toe]]. {{citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\n===Vehicles===\n[[File:1999 Buick Riviera.jpg|250px|right|thumb|1999 Buick Riviera]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Years\n!Wheelbase\n!Model\n!Platform Name*\n|-\n|1995\u20131999||113.8&nbsp;in||[[Buick Riviera]]||GM G platform\n|-\n|1995\u20131999||113.8&nbsp;in||[[Oldsmobile Aurora]]||GM G platform\n|-\n|1997-2005||113.8&nbsp;in||[[Buick Park Avenue]]||[[GM C platform (1985)|GM C platform]]\n|-\n|1998\u20132004||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Cadillac Seville]]||[[GM K platform (1980)|GM K platform]]\n|-\n|2000\u20132005||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Buick LeSabre]]||[[GM H platform (1986)|GM H platform]]\n|-\n|2000\u20132005||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Pontiac Bonneville]]||[[GM H platform (1986)|GM H platform]]\n|-\n|2001\u20132003||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Oldsmobile Aurora]]||GM G platform\n|-\n|2000\u20132005||115.3&nbsp;in||[[Cadillac DeVille]]||[[GM K platform (1980)|GM K platform]]\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> Official designation given by GM, despite using a G platform-derivative. This name also corresponds to the 4th letter in the [[VIN]] of the vehicle.\n\n==Revision==\nThe G platform was updated for the 2006 model year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Buick Lucerne|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/news/buick-lucerne-auto-shows|work=[[Car and Driver]]|accessdate=17 May 2013|date=February 2005}}</ref>  The final car on this platform was the [[Buick Lucerne]], which ended production in June 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.just-auto.com/news/gm-axes-cadillac-dts-and-buick-lucerne_id111499.aspx|title=US: GM axes Cadillac DTS and Buick Lucerne|publisher=just-auto.com |date=2011-05-26 |accessdate=2011-06-05}}</ref>\n\n===Vehicles===\n[[File:Buick-Lucerne.jpg|right|thumb|2006 Buick Lucerne]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Years\n!Wheelbase\n!Model\n!Platform Name*\n|-\n|2006\u20132011||115.6&nbsp;in||[[Cadillac DTS]]||[[GM K platform (1980)|GM K platform]]\n|-\n|2006\u20132011||115.6&nbsp;in||[[Buick Lucerne]]||[[GM H platform (1986)|GM H platform]]\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> Official designation given by GM, despite using a G platform-derivative. This name also corresponds to the 4th letter in the [[VIN]] of the vehicle.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[http://pp.kpnet.fi/haydee/GM_VIN_codes.htm List of GM VIN codes]\n{{General Motors platforms}}\n\n[[Category:General Motors platforms|G 2]]\n", "name_user": "2605:e000:1528:436f:141e:5482:ea65:5a94", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GM_G_platform_(1995)"}
{"title_page": "Eleanor de Bohun, Countess of Ormonde", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Eleanor de Bohun\n| title = Countess of Ormond\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[James Butler, 1st Earl of Ormond]]|1327|1337|end=d}}<br>{{marriage|[[Thomas Dagworth|Thomas de Dagworth, Lord Dagworth]]|1343|1352|end=d}}\n| issue = John Butler<br />Petronilla Butler<br />[[James Butler, 2nd Earl of Ormond]]<br />Eleanor de Dagworth\n| father = [[Humphrey de Bohun, 4th Earl of Hereford]]\n| mother = [[Elizabeth of Rhuddlan]]\n| birth_date = 17 October 1304\n| birth_place  = [[Knaresborough Castle]], [[Knaresborough]], [[North Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date = {{dda|1363|10|7|1304|10|17|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Aldgate]], [[Middlesex]], England\n| burial_place = Chapel of Saint Edmunds, [[Westminster Abbey]]\n}}\n'''Eleanor de Bohun, Countess of Ormond''' (17 October 1304 &ndash; 7 October 1363) was an English noblewoman born in [[Knaresborough Castle]] to [[Humphrey de Bohun, 4th Earl of Hereford]], and [[Elizabeth of Rhuddlan|Elizabeth]], daughter of King [[Edward I of England]] and [[Eleanor of Castile]]. After the deaths of her parents, she was placed in the care of her aunt [[Mary of Woodstock]] and brought up at [[Amesbury Priory]] alongside various cousins including Joan Gaveston, Isabel of Lancaster and Joan de Monthermer. [[Edward II of England]] gave the priory a generous allowance of 100 marks annually for the upkeep of Eleanor and her younger cousin, Joan Gaveston.<ref name=\"edwardthesecond.blogspot.com\">http://edwardthesecond.blogspot.com/2007/02/eleanor-and-margaret-de-bohun.html</ref>\n\nEleanor was married twice; first in 1327 to [[James Butler, 1st Earl of Ormond]], (son of [[Edmund Butler, Earl of Carrick]], and [[Joan FitzGerald|Lady Joan FitzGerald]]) who died in 1337 and secondly, six years later in 1343, to [[Thomas Dagworth|Thomas de Dagworth, Lord Dagworth]], who was killed in an ambush in Brittany in 1352.\n\n==Children==\nBy James Butler:\n* John Butler (born 6 November 1330, died young)\n* Petronilla (or Perina) Butler, Baroness Talbot (died 1387) who married [[Gilbert Talbot, 3rd Baron Talbot]] and had a daughter, Elizabeth Talbot, who married [[Baron Grey of Wilton|Sir Henry de Grey of Wilton, 5th Baron Grey de Wilton]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Richardson|first=Douglas|title=Magna Carta ancestry : a study in colonial and medieval families|year=2011|publisher=Douglas Richardson.|location=Salt Lake City, UT.|isbn=9781460992708|pages=165\u2013166, 345\u2013346|edition=2nd}}</ref> \n* [[James Butler, 2nd Earl of Ormond]] (4 October 1331 \u2013 18 October 1382) who married [[Elizabeth Darcy, Countess of Ormond|Elizabeth Darcy]]\n\nBy Thomas de Dagworth:\n* Eleanor de Dagworth who married at Vachery (in Cranley), Surrey by licence dated 23 June 1362 Walter Fitz Walter, Knt, [[Baron_FitzWalter|3rd Lord Fitz Walter]] (1345\u20131386). Eleanor was living 29 Nov 1375. At her death, she was buried in Dunmow Priory.<ref>Douglas Richardson, Magna Carta Ancestry, p.347</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Butler dynasty]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[http://www.thepeerage.com/p10694.htm#i106939 thepeerage.com] Accessed 22 March 2008\n*[http://edwardthesecond.blogspot.com/2007/02/eleanor-and-margaret-de-bohun.html Eleanor de Bohun] Accessed 23 March 2008\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ormonde, Eleanor de Bohun, Countess of}}\n[[Category:1304 births]]\n[[Category:1363 deaths]]\n[[Category:Butler dynasty|Eleanor]]\n[[Category:People from Knaresborough]]\n[[Category:Bohun family|Eleanor]]\n[[Category:British countesses]]\n[[Category:14th-century English women]]\n[[Category:14th-century English people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Eleanor de Bohun\n| title = Countess of Ormond\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[James Butler, 1st Earl of Ormond]]|1327|1337|end=d}}<br>{{marriage|[[Thomas Dagworth|Thomas de Dagworth, Lord Dagworth]]|1343|1352|end=d}}\n| issue = John Butler<br />Petronilla Butler<br />[[James Butler, 2nd Earl of Ormond]]<br />Eleanor de Dagworth\n| father = [[Humphrey de Bohun, 4th Earl of Hereford]]\n| mother = [[Elizabeth of Rhuddlan]]\n| birth_date = 17 October 1304\n| birth_place  = [[Knaresborough Castle]], [[Knaresborough]], [[North Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date = {{dda|1363|10|7|1304|10|17|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Aldgate]], [[Middlesex]], England\n| burial_place = Chapel of Saint Edmunds, [[Westminster Abbey]]\n}}\n'''Eleanor de Bohun, Countess of Ormond''' (17 October 1304 &ndash; 7 October 1363) was an English noblewoman born in [[Knaresborough Castle]] to [[Humphrey de Bohun, 4th Earl of Hereford]], and [[Elizabeth of Rhuddlan|Elizabeth]], daughter of King [[Edward I of England]] and [[Eleanor of Castile]]. After the deaths of her parents, she was placed in the care of her aunt [[Mary of Woodstock]] and brought up at [[Amesbury Priory]] alongside various cousins including Joan Gaveston, Isabel of Lancaster and Joan de Monthermer. [[Edward II of England]] gave the priory a generous allowance of 100 marks annually for the upkeep of Eleanor and her younger cousin, Joan Gaveston.<ref name=\"edwardthesecond.blogspot.com\">http://edwardthesecond.blogspot.com/2007/02/eleanor-and-margaret-de-bohun.html</ref>\n\nEleanor was married twice; first in 1327 to [[James Butler, 1st Earl of Ormond]], (son of [[Edmund Butler, Earl of Carrick]], and [[Joan FitzGerald|Lady Joan FitzGerald]]) who died in 1337 and secondly, six years later in 1343, to [[Thomas Dagworth|Thomas de Dagworth, Lord Dagworth]] who was killed in an ambush in Brittany in 1352.\n\n==Children==\nBy James Butler:\n* John Butler (born 6 November 1330, died young)\n* Petronilla (or Perina) Butler, Baroness Talbot (died 1387) who married [[Gilbert Talbot, 3rd Baron Talbot]] and had a daughter, Elizabeth Talbot, who married [[Baron Grey of Wilton|Sir Henry de Grey of Wilton, 5th Baron Grey de Wilton]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Richardson|first=Douglas|title=Magna Carta ancestry : a study in colonial and medieval families|year=2011|publisher=Douglas Richardson.|location=Salt Lake City, UT.|isbn=9781460992708|pages=165\u2013166, 345\u2013346|edition=2nd}}</ref> \n* [[James Butler, 2nd Earl of Ormond]] (4 October 1331 \u2013 18 October 1382) who married [[Elizabeth Darcy, Countess of Ormond|Elizabeth Darcy]]\n\nBy Thomas de Dagworth:\n* Eleanor de Dagworth who married at Vachery (in Cranley), Surrey by licence dated 23 June 1362 Walter Fitz Walter, Knt, [[Baron_FitzWalter|3rd Lord Fitz Walter]] (1345\u20131386). Eleanor was living 29 Nov 1375. At her death, she was buried in Dunmow Priory.<ref>Douglas Richardson, Magna Carta Ancestry, p.347</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Butler dynasty]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[http://www.thepeerage.com/p10694.htm#i106939 thepeerage.com] Accessed 22 March 2008\n*[http://edwardthesecond.blogspot.com/2007/02/eleanor-and-margaret-de-bohun.html Eleanor de Bohun] Accessed 23 March 2008\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ormonde, Eleanor de Bohun, Countess of}}\n[[Category:1304 births]]\n[[Category:1363 deaths]]\n[[Category:Butler dynasty|Eleanor]]\n[[Category:People from Knaresborough]]\n[[Category:Bohun family|Eleanor]]\n[[Category:British countesses]]\n[[Category:14th-century English women]]\n[[Category:14th-century English people]]\n", "name_user": "Iamthecheese44", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eleanor_de_Bohun,_Countess_of_Ormonde"}
